        "Description/Abstract": "Energy, water, and food resources are intertwined. Globally, 60-80%\nof water resources are used in agriculture. Food supply chain claims up\nto 30% of the global energy production. Energy production is also highly\nwater dependent, with an average of around 95 liters of water withdrawal\nper kWh. Modeling the complex interactions at the nexus of energy, water,\nand food is crucial for human well-being, sustainable development\nand policymaking. In this study, we have developed an interactive analysis\ntoolbox that mines the available global data at the nexus of energy,\nwater, and food and models/analyzes their interdependencies at the country\nlevel. This toolbox, entitled the Nexus of Energy, Water, and Food\n(NEWF), estimates the water footprint for several food types and approximates\nthe energy required for a user-specified quantity of water, as\nwell as the associated potential food production. NEWF also estimates\nthe emissions associated with different energy sources, provides a rough\nappraisal of required water to produce/extract/refine energy, and finally\napproximates the biofuel production of different crops.",
        "Origin": "Manual"
